article.description:
Tamika Catchings' availability to start for
the East in the WNBA All-Star Game on Monday became uncertain Friday
night when the Indiana rookie suffered a concussion.
article.headline: Catchings might have suffered broken nose in defeat
article.linkText: Miami knocks out Indiana and Catchings
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Tamika Catchings' availability to start for
the East in the WNBA All-Star Game on Monday became uncertain Friday
night when the Indiana rookie suffered a concussion.

	   Catchings was injured when Miami's Ruth Riley struck her with an
elbow in the first half of the Sol's 68-62 victory.

	   Miami shot 48 percent in the second half, while Indiana's
offense struggled without its star to finish the second half at 36
percent.

	   Indiana's team physician, Dr. David Harsha, said Catchings might have broken her nose.

	   ''She did sustain a mild concussion, and we will be monitoring
her, although it looks like she came through OK,'' he said. ''We
will keep her comfortable overnight and reevaluate her status for
the All-Star Game.''

	   Indiana coach Nell Fortner was confident Catchings would be able
to play in the game.

	   ''Wild horses and steel bars will be needed to keep Tamika from
playing,'' Fortner said. ''They will have to handcuff her to the
chair to prevent her from playing.''

	   It was Miami's sixth consecutive victory over the Fever, and
Miami coach Ron Rothstein agreed that Indiana was hurt by
Catchings' absence.

	   ''You lose a great player, it hurts; there's no two ways about
it,'' Rothstein said. ''You can't lose a great player like her.
She's such a focal part of everything that they do.''

	   Catchings fell to the court when Riley's elbow landed on her
nose.

	   The crowd screamed for a foul as Catchings remained on the
floor, but the three officials did not see the play and let the
game continue.

	   The Sol led 23-20 with 6:52 left in the first half when
Catchings went down. Riley got the ball and made a layup before
Indiana called a 20-second timeout to get treatment for their star
and to protest the lack of a call.

	   ''That was a tough foul. There's no question it was an offensive
foul. Very unfortunate,'' Fortner said.

	   Catchings, second in the league in scoring with an 18.4 average
and fourth in rebounding at 8.5, never returned to the game and
finished with six points and two rebounds.

	   Indiana overcame a seven-point deficit in the first half to lead
33-31 at the break, but was unable to overcome the Sol defense and
the loss of their star in the second half.

	   ''She came down to double and as I turned I hit her. Obviously
it was an accident. I feel horrible about it,'' Riley said.

	   Miami, which won for the sixth time in seven games, took the
lead for good with a 9-1 run to start the second half.

	   Miami (8-10) took a 53-40 lead with 8:39 to play when Sheri Sam
made a layup and Betty Lennox hit a free throw after Fortner drew a
technical foul.

	   Indiana (8-11) fell behind by 14 points when Sandy Brondello was
fouled attempting a 3-pointer and made all the free throws to give
the Sol a 56-42 lead. Indiana cut its deficit to 66-62 in the final
minute, but was unable to draw any closer.

	   Sam finished with 15 points and 10 rebounds, while Brondello had
14 points and Lennox and Riley added 10 each.

	   ''We came out in the second half with more intensity,'' said
Brondello, who had seven of her 10 second-half points as the Sol
moved ahead early in the period. ''When we pick up the intensity,
everything flows and the defense sets up the offense.''

	   Nadine Malcolm led Indiana with 16 points and Olympia
Scott-Richardson had 14 points and 11 rebounds.
